one of those teenage things,
but she simply said

277
00:13:00,647 --> 00:13:03,383
that she owed it all
to her friends, the digimon.

278
00:13:03,416 --> 00:13:05,151
‐ Her friends the digimon?

279
00:13:05,184 --> 00:13:07,453
‐ That's right, her adventures
with them forced her

280
00:13:07,487 --> 00:13:09,589
to grow up and change her
outlook on everything.

281
00:13:09,622 --> 00:13:12,225
Especially the stormy
relationship with her mother.

282
00:13:12,258 --> 00:13:15,094
You should see them now,
shopping every Saturday,

283
00:13:15,128 --> 00:13:16,629
my credit card's at the limit!

284
00:13:16,663 --> 00:13:18,231
‐ Oh.

285
00:13:18,264 --> 00:13:21,734
‐ So thanks to the digimon,
our family is a lot closer now,

286
00:13:21,768 --> 00:13:23,903
even though
I'm still never around.

287
00:13:23,936 --> 00:13:25,705
‐ You're welcome!

288
00:13:25,738 --> 00:13:26,906
‐ That's a beautiful story.

289
00:13:26,939 --> 00:13:28,708
Thanks for sharing.

290
00:13:28,741 --> 00:13:30,943
‐ I'm glad I'm getting to see
a digimon on a friendly basis.

291
00:13:30,977 --> 00:13:32,679
I've had a run‐in with
them before, you know.

292
00:13:32,712 --> 00:13:34,013
When everything happened
three years ago,

293
00:13:34,047 --> 00:13:35,548
I was right in the
middle of the battle.

294
00:13:35,581 --> 00:13:37,450
Actually, my brother Joe
was a little more involved.

295
00:13:37,483 --> 00:13:39,519
I was sorta helping
from the sidelines.

296
00:13:39,552 --> 00:13:41,387
It's not that I couldn't have
helped him fight, it's just

297
00:13:41,421 --> 00:13:43,890
that I wanted to give the kid
a chance to learn on his own.

298
00:13:43,923 --> 00:13:45,291
‐ I still don't get it.

299
00:13:45,325 --> 00:13:46,826
Of all the cities
they could've picked,

300
00:13:46,859 --> 00:13:50,096
why did the digimon start
showing up here in Kyoto?

301
00:13:50,129 --> 00:13:52,131
‐ Ever since Kyoto
became the capital,

302
00:13:52,165 --> 00:13:54,200
residents here feel
the city has developed

303
00:13:54,233 --> 00:13:56,636
a very strong connection
with animal spirits.

304
00:13:56,669 --> 00:13:58,271
‐ What?

305
00:13:58,304 --> 00:14:01,007
‐ That's right, different
animals like raccoons and foxes.

306
00:14:01,040 --> 00:14:03,009
One of the reasons
I'm here is to determine

307
00:14:03,042 --> 00:14:05,011
if these stories
are based on fact.

308
00:14:05,044 --> 00:14:07,146
Another reason is
there's an outlet mall

309
00:14:07,180 --> 00:14:08,815
where I can get my
socks for half price.

310
00:14:08,848 --> 00:14:10,583
‐ I see.

311
00:14:10,616 --> 00:14:12,819
PROFESSOR: Kyoto was chosen
to be the capital partly

312
00:14:12,852 --> 00:14:16,289
because the four gods are in
harmony surrounding the city.

313
00:14:16,322 --> 00:14:19,859
Have you heard that story?
‐ I'm not sure.

314
00:14:19,892 --> 00:14:21,327
PROFESSOR: It's
quite interesting.

315
00:14:21,361 --> 00:14:22,962
You see, the mountains
to the north are for

316
00:14:22,995 --> 00:14:24,263
Genbu the turtle, the river

317
00:14:24,297 --> 00:14:27,367
to the east is for
Seiryuu the dragon,

318
00:14:27,400 --> 00:14:30,169
the river to the south
is for Suzaku the phoenix,

319
00:14:30,203 --> 00:14:33,639
and the road to the west
is for Byakko the tiger.

320
00:14:33,673 --> 00:14:35,441
So the city was protected
by the mountains,

321
00:14:35,475 --> 00:14:37,443
had the convenience of
a river and roads nearby,

322
00:14:37,477 --> 00:14:39,712
and was open to the west.
A perfect scenario.

323
00:14:39,746 --> 00:14:41,214
‐ Cool.

324
00:14:41,247 --> 00:14:42,715
‐ There's also the Spirit Gate,
and the fact that

325
00:14:42,749 --> 00:14:47,286
there were many temples
built in all four directions.

326
00:14:47,320 --> 00:14:48,888
They believe that
without those temples,

327
00:14:48,921 --> 00:14:51,924
it'd be too easy for the
magical creatures to get in.

328
00:14:51,958 --> 00:14:53,659
‐ Spirits?

329
00:14:53,693 --> 00:14:55,561
Creatures?

330
00:14:55,595 --> 00:14:56,662
‐ Professor!

331
00:14:56,696 --> 00:14:57,830
‐ Oh, I'm sorry.

332
00:14:57,864 --> 00:14:59,298
I didn't mean to scare you.

333
00:14:59,332 --> 00:15:01,868
Sometimes I get wrapped
up in my own stories.

334
00:15:01,901 --> 00:15:05,271
The city has changed
a lot since those days.

335
00:15:05,304 --> 00:15:08,574
What I'm trying to say is
that Kyoto is close to the

336
00:15:08,608 --> 00:15:12,245
spirit world, in other words,
any world other than our own.

337
00:15:12,278 --> 00:15:14,247
‐ Like the Digital World?

338
00:15:14,280 --> 00:15:17,316
‐ I have a theory that those
digimon you saw running around

339
00:15:17,350 --> 00:15:19,452
found it easier to travel
through the warp in the

340
00:15:19,485 --> 00:15:22,889
Digital World to Kyoto rather
than trying to go to Tokyo.

341
00:15:22,922 --> 00:15:26,092
‐ Wait a minute, are you
trying to tell me that digimon

342
00:15:26,125 --> 00:15:28,828
are some sort of
magical creatures?

343
00:15:28,861 --> 00:15:30,563
‐ Well aren't they?
‐ Huh?

344
00:15:30,596 --> 00:15:32,832
‐ It's not like they're
just a collection of data.

345
00:15:32,865 --> 00:15:35,501
I believe that digimon are
actually legends that people

346
00:15:35,535 --> 00:15:39,071
have spoken of for hundreds
of years, and, over time,

347
00:15:39,105 --> 00:15:41,707
have gained a level
of consciousness

348
00:15:41,741 --> 00:15:43,309
and become a reality.

349
00:15:44,377 --> 00:15:46,679
I think that digimon
may have started

350
00:15:46,712 --> 00:15:50,116
as data in some old computer,
but have since come alive.

351
00:15:50,149 --> 00:15:52,218
Just like those old legends.

352
00:15:52,251 --> 00:15:54,654
Do you agree with my theory?

353
00:15:56,055 --> 00:15:58,057
‐ Uh, huh?

354
00:15:58,090 --> 00:16:00,927
( surprised cry )

355
00:16:00,960 --> 00:16:04,564
